quran[23]{c,v,t,f}:
51,52,"Thus has it been (in the past): never did a Messenger come to the nations that preceded them but they said: “(He is) a sorcerer, or a mad-man.” {1}",footnotes:1:That is
51,53,"Have they arrived at a common understanding concerning this? No; but they are a people given to transgression. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
51,54,"So turn your attention away from them; you shall incur no blame. {1}",footnotes:1:In this verse a method of the preaching of religion has been taught which should be well understood. When a preacher of the truth has presented his message clearly before a person with rational arguments
51,55,"Do, however, keep exhorting them; for exhortation benefits those endowed with faith. {1}",footnotes:1:The Prophet (peace be upon him) has not been addressed here to be taught this method because
51,56,"I created the jinn and humans for nothing else but that they may serve Me; {1}",footnotes:1:That is
51,57,"I desire from them no provision, nor do I want them to feed Me. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
51,58,"Surely Allah is the Bestower of all provision, the Lord of all power, the Strong. {1}",footnotes:1:The word mateen as used in the original means strong and stable whom nobody can shake and move.
51,59,"The wrong-doers {1} shall receive a portion of the chastisements as their fellows (of yore). So let them not rush Me.",footnotes:1:Those who have wronged: Those who have violated the reality and the truth and their own nature. The context itself shows that those who have done wrong
51,60,"Woe, then, betide those who disbelieved in that Day of theirs which they are being asked to hold in dread."
52,1,"By the Mount, {1}",footnotes:1:Toor means a mountain
52,2,"and the Book inscribed"
52,3,"on fine parchment; {1}",footnotes:1:In ancient times the books and writings which were meant to be preserved for long were written on the skin of deer instead of the paper. This skin was especially prepared for writing as a thin and fine parchment and was called raqq terminologically. The Jews and Christians in general wrote the Torah
52,4,"by the much-frequented House, {1}",footnotes:1:According to Hasan Basri
52,5,"by the elevated canopy; {1}",footnotes:1:The roof exalted: the sky which seems to be spread over the earth like a vault; here this word has been used for the entire universe. (For explanation
52,6,"and by the swelling sea: {1}",footnotes:1:Several meanings have ban given of the word al-bahrilmasjur as used in the original. Some commentators have taken it in the meaning of full of fire; some take it in the sense of empty and unoccupied
52,7,"verily your Lord's chastisement shall come to pass,"
52,8,"none can avert that. {1}",footnotes:1:This is that truth for which an oath has been sworn by the five things. “The punishment of your Lord” implies the Hereafter
52,9,"(It shall come to pass) on the Day when the heaven will convulse in a great convulsion, {1}",footnotes:1:The word maur in the original is used for turning round
52,10,"and the mountains shall violently fly about. {1}",footnotes:1:In other words
52,11,"Woe, then, on that Day to those who give the lie (to this Message)"
52,12,"and amuse themselves with vain argumentation. {1}",footnotes:1:It means that they are mocking and ridiculing the news of Resurrection
52,13,"On the Day when they shall be thrust into Hell with a violent thrust (and shall be told):"
52,14,"“This is the Hell which you used to give the lie to.”"
